d 'CHSE': module implementing Contested Hierarchy with Social Embedding
d
d  We develop a theory of hierarchical authority in which
d leadership is contested, not structural. Hierarchy beliefs (the
d probability that player i leads player j) evolve through four
d coupled mechanisms: Bayesian anticipation, role ambiguity,
d retroactive reframing, and network propagation via an endogenous
d kernel. The solution concept is the Hierarchy Orbit Equilibrium
d (HOE), an invariant measure of the induced Markov process,
d nesting Nash and Stackelberg as degenerate special cases. We show
d that a 15-parameter system compresses into two indices: the
d Hierarchy Stability Index and Propagation Intensity, whose ratio
d partitions parameter space into four dynamic regimes. We prove
d existence, ergodicity, and Lyapunov stability, and characterise
d three welfare distortions endemic to interior equilibria. A
d central result is the Hierarchy Persistence Paradox: stronger
d hierarchies produce larger cascades when they fall, because
d accumulated anticipation accuracy inflates the spectral radius of
d the propagation kernel. Applied to central bank independence, the
d framework correctly classifies six country-period episodes from
d robust monetary dominance to fiscal dominance. 
d
d KW: contested hierarchy
d KW: social embedding
d
d Requires: Stata version 14
d
d Distribution-Date: 20260418
d
